    "notes": "Sea eel / whitespotted conger (Conger myriaster). Always cooked.\n\nAnago vs hamo — both saltwater conger-family eels, very different traditions:\n  • Location: Anago is Edo-mae (Tokyo Bay); hamo is Kansai (Kyoto / Osaka / Setouchi).\n  • Season: Anago is year-round but historically winter prime; hamo is the SUMMER fish (peaks at Kyoto's Gion Matsuri in July).\n  • Flavour: Anago is fattier, softer, sweetly umami from the tare; hamo is leaner, lighter, faintly sweet.\n  • Prep: Anago is simmered in sweet broth and lightly grilled with tare (no bone problem); hamo demands honegiri (bone-cutting) and is most often blanched (yubiki) and served chilled with plum sauce. Both always cooked.\n\nVs unagi: this is the other key comparison. Anago = sea eel, simmered in sweet broth then lightly grilled with tare; lighter, fluffier, more delicate. Unagi = freshwater eel, grilled (sometimes steamed too) with much heavier sweet tare; richer, more decadent. Anago is the Edo-mae specialty; unagi is the izakaya/donburi star. Vs noresore: noresore is the juvenile of conger eels — translucent, jelly-like, raw.\n\nCommon, mid. The famous 'two pieces, two sauces' Edo-mae presentation: half the slice with sweet tare, the other half with a sprinkle of salt to taste the fish itself. Tokyo Bay anago is the prestige source.",
