    "detail": "Muraenesox cinereus",
    "certainty": "Precise-ish",
    "notes": "Pike conger (Muraenesox cinereus). A different eel than anago, with a wildly different prep tradition.\n\nPrep — the iconic two-step Kyoto technique:\n  1. HONEGIRI (骨切り, \"bone-cutting\"): hamo's flesh is laced with hundreds of tiny pin bones too small to remove individually. The chef lays the fillet skin-side-down and makes ~1mm-spaced cuts down through the flesh and bones, stopping precisely at the skin so the fillet stays in one piece. A skilled chef can make 24+ cuts per inch. The cuts crush the bones into edibility without damaging the structure. This is one of the showcase knife techniques of Kansai cuisine.\n  2. YUBIKI (湯引き, hot-water blanching): the bone-cut fillet is briefly plunged into boiling water (or boiling water poured over it) — the cut sections curl outward and the meat \"blooms\" like a white chrysanthemum or peony (botan-zukuri). Then immediately shocked in ice water.\n\nCommon dishes (almost all built on the honegiri+yubiki base):\n  • Hamo no otoshi / hamo-yubiki — the iconic chilled blanched-bloomed hamo, served with umeboshi-ae (plum sauce) or sumiso (vinegared miso). The defining Kyoto summer dish, especially at Gion Matsuri (July).\n  • Hamo no tsukuri — raw sashimi-style thin slices (rarer; needs the freshest fish).\n  • Hamo-shabu — briefly swished in dashi hot pot.\n  • Hamo-suki / hamo-nabe — full hot pot with vegetables.\n  • Hamo-yaki / kabayaki — grilled, sometimes with tare like unagi.\n  • Hamo-ten — tempura. Honegiri still required first; the battered fried result is light and airy with the characteristic bone-cut texture inside. A summer feature at Kansai tempura specialty restaurants and an occasional kaiseki agemono course.\n\nHamo vs anago — both saltwater conger-family eels, but very different traditions:\n  • Location: Hamo is Kansai (Kyoto / Osaka / Setouchi); anago is Edo-mae (Tokyo Bay).\n  • Season: Hamo is the SUMMER fish (peaks at Kyoto's Gion Matsuri in July); anago is year-round but historically winter prime.\n  • Flavour: Hamo is leaner, lighter, faintly sweet; anago is fattier, softer, sweetly umami from the tare.\n  • Prep: Hamo demands honegiri (bone-cutting) and is most often blanched (yubiki) and served chilled with plum sauce; anago is simmered in sweet broth and lightly grilled with tare. Both always cooked.\n\nVs unagi: hamo is leaner, lighter, and not lacquered with sweet tare. The bone-cut hamo's chrysanthemum-bloom yubiki visual is unique among the eels.\n\nLess common at sushi counters, mid–premium. Almost always a kaiseki / Kyoto-restaurant fish rather than a sushi-counter fish. Cultural icon of Gion Matsuri.",
