    "notes": "True mirugai = Tresus keenae / Asian gaper clam.\n\nPrep: the long siphon (the dark elephant-trunk-like part that protrudes from the shell) is the prized cut. The chef removes the dark outer skin from the siphon (sometimes by briefly scalding it with boiling water, then peeling), then slices the white inner meat thin and serves it RAW as nigiri or sashimi. The natural snap of the siphon's muscle wall gives the iconic crunchy bite. Sometimes the meat is also briefly blanched (yu-bi-ki) for a slight texture tightening, but pure raw is the prestige presentation.\n\nMirugai (mirukui) vs namigai (shiromiru) breakdown — the central name-confusion of Japanese sushi shellfish:\n  • Color: Mirugai has DARKER skin and siphon; namigai is whiter / brighter.\n  • Price: Mirugai is very high (premium); namigai is moderate / affordable.\n  • Flavor: Mirugai is deep, sweet, with strong sea flavor; namigai is mild, sweet, delicate.\n  • Rarity: True mirugai is rare and increasingly endangered; namigai is the common alternative.\n  • How eaten: Both are prepared the same way — the long siphon is the prized cut, the dark outer skin is peeled (sometimes after a brief scald), the white inner meat is sliced thin and served RAW as nigiri or sashimi. Sometimes briefly blanched (yu-bi-ki) for a slight texture tightening. Pure raw is the prestige presentation; never fully cooked at sushi counters.\n\nAt high-end Japanese sushi counters \"mirugai\" means real Tresus; everywhere else (overseas, supermarkets, conveyor sushi) what's labeled \"mirugai\" is almost certainly namigai (Pacific geoduck). Vs akagai: mirugai is the long-siphon-clam category, akagai is whole-body. Vs hokkigai: both crunchy, but mirugai's siphon meat is firmer and more oceanic.\n\nPremium, less common. Crunchy, briny, deeply oceanic.",
