    "notes": "Pacific geoduck (Panopea generosa). Often nicknamed \"shiromiru\" (white miru) on Japanese menus, contrasting with the darker true mirugai.\n\nPrep: same approach as true mirugai — the long siphon is what's eaten. The chef peels off the dark outer skin (sometimes by briefly scalding then peeling), slices the white inner meat thin, and serves it RAW as nigiri or sashimi. The central snap of the muscle wall is the textural payoff. Occasionally briefly blanched (yu-bi-ki) for a slight texture tightening. The BC and Washington-state geoduck export industry is the main supply for what's sold as \"mirugai\" in Japan and abroad.\n\nNamigai (shiromiru) vs mirugai (mirukui) breakdown — namigai is what you'll usually actually be eating:\n  • Color: Namigai has WHITER / brighter siphon; mirugai's skin and siphon are darker.\n  • Price: Namigai is moderate / affordable; mirugai is very high (premium).\n  • Flavor: Namigai is mild, sweet, delicate; mirugai is deep, sweet, with stronger sea flavor.\n  • Rarity: Namigai is the common alternative; true mirugai is rare and increasingly endangered.\n  • How eaten: Both are prepared identically — the long siphon is the prized cut, the dark outer skin is peeled (sometimes after a brief scald), the white inner meat is sliced thin and served RAW as nigiri or sashimi. Sometimes briefly blanched (yu-bi-ki) for a slight texture tightening. Outside sushi, namigai also shows up in Cantonese geoduck-sashimi presentations (often with hot-pot cooking of the body) and Western geoduck preparations because of the high supply.\n\nThis is the species commonly SOLD as \"mirugai\" abroad and at most non-premium counters — they're using the more famous name for marketing reasons, not because the species are the same. Vs other clams: namigai has the longest, most siphon-prominent profile.\n\nCommon, mid. Crunchy and briny.",
