    "notes": "Generic whelk (Buccinum). Crunchy sea snail living in a spiral shell.\n\nPrep: usually served RAW as nigiri or thin sashimi slices at sushi counters. The chef extracts the meat from the spiral shell with a twist (the natural spiral helps it pull free as a single curled piece), then performs a critical step — removing the salivary gland (a small yellowish lump embedded in the muscle), which contains tetramine, a mildly toxic compound that causes dizziness, nausea, and headaches if eaten. The meat is then sliced thin against the muscle fibers to manage the dense chewiness. Outside sushiya, tsubugai is also boiled briefly and served chilled with vinegar dressing (su-no-mono), grilled in shell at izakaya (tsubu-yaki, similar to sazae's tsubo-yaki), or simmered. The raw nigiri is the standard sushi presentation.\n\nVs sazae (turban shell): tsubugai is more common and smaller; sazae is bigger, bitterer, and almost always grilled in-shell rather than served raw. Vs baigai (ivory shell): similar 'crunchy small sea snail' tier but baigai is sweeter and also typically raw at sushiya. Vs akagai: both crunchy, but tsubugai is a snail (univalve) while akagai is a clam (bivalve) — different family.\n\nCommon at sushi counters, budget–mid. Crunchy, mildly briny, slightly sweet.",
